<hr class="section-divider">

<!-- SECTION 1 -->
<h1 id="overview">1. Project Overview</h1>

<p>Estate Management is a full-stack real estate platform with three separate services that run together:</p>

<table>
  <tr>
    <th>Service</th>
    <th>URL</th>
    <th>Who Uses It</th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><strong>Frontend</strong></td>
    <td>http://localhost:5173</td>
    <td>Buyers and sellers — browse properties, register, login, add listings, book viewings</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><strong>Admin Panel</strong></td>
    <td>http://localhost:5174</td>
    <td>Administrators — manage all listings, users, appointments, and analytics</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><strong>Backend API</strong></td>
    <td>http://localhost:4000</td>
    <td>Internal API — the frontend and admin both connect to this</td>
  </tr>
</table>

<p>The three services start together with a single command from the root folder.</p>

<hr class="section-divider">

<!-- SECTION 2 -->
<h1 id="installation">2. Installation &amp; Setup</h1>

<h2>2.1 Prerequisites</h2>

<p>Before starting, make sure you have these installed on your machine:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Node.js 18 or later</strong> — download from <code>nodejs.org</code></li>
  <li><strong>npm 8 or later</strong> — included with Node.js</li>
  <li><strong>MongoDB</strong> — either a local installation or a free MongoDB Atlas cluster</li>
  <li><strong>Git</strong> — to clone the repository</li>
</ul>

<p>To verify your versions, open a terminal and run:</p>
<pre>node --version
npm --version</pre>

<h2>2.2 Clone the Repository</h2>

<pre>git clone https://github.com/mikey-harsh/Real-Estate-Management-System.git
cd Real-Estate-Management-System</pre>

<h2>2.3 Install All Dependencies</h2>

<p>Run this single command from the root folder. It installs dependencies for all three services (backend, frontend, admin) at once:</p>

<pre>npm install</pre>

<div class="note">
  <strong>Note:</strong> This may take 2–4 minutes the first time. You will see output from three separate <code>npm install</code> runs.
</div>

<h2>2.4 Configure the Backend Environment</h2>

<p>The backend needs a <code>.env.local</code> file. One already exists at <code>backend/.env.local</code> with default values for local development.</p>

<p>Open <code>backend/.env.local</code> and check these key values:</p>

<table>
  <tr>
    <th>Variable</th>
    <th>Default Value</th>
    <th>What It Does</th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>MONGO_URI</code></td>
    <td>mongodb://localhost:27017/estate-management</td>
    <td>MongoDB connection string. Change if using Atlas.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>JWT_SECRET</code></td>
    <td>estatemanagement_dev_jwt_secret…</td>
    <td>Secret key for signing login tokens. Keep private.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>ADMIN_EMAIL</code></td>
    <td>admin@estatemanagement.com</td>
    <td>Email used to log into the admin dashboard.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>ADMIN_PASSWORD</code></td>
    <td>Admin@123456</td>
    <td>Password used to log into the admin dashboard.</td>
  </tr>
</table>

<p>For a basic local setup, the defaults work without any changes.</p>

<hr class="section-divider">

<!-- SECTION 3 -->
<h1 id="starting">3. Starting the Application</h1>

<p>From the root project folder, run:</p>

<pre>npm run dev</pre>

<p>This starts all three services simultaneously. Wait until you see output like:</p>

<pre>[backend]   Server running on http://localhost:4000
[frontend]  Local: http://localhost:5173
[admin]     Local: http://localhost:5174</pre>

<p>Now open your browser and go to <strong>http://localhost:5173</strong> to see the main website.</p>

<div class="note">
  <strong>Tip:</strong> Keep this terminal window open. Closing it will stop all three services.
</div>

<hr class="section-divider">

<!-- SECTION 4 -->
<h1 id="admin-setup">4. Creating the Admin Account</h1>

<p>The admin account must be created once before you can log into the admin dashboard. Open a <strong>new terminal window</strong> (keep the <code>npm run dev</code> terminal running) and run:</p>

<pre>cd backend
node scripts/createAdmin.js</pre>

<p>You should see:</p>
<pre>Connected to MongoDB
Admin user created successfully
Email: admin@estatemanagement.com</pre>

<p>The admin credentials are:</p>
<div class="credential-box">
  URL:       http://localhost:5174<br>
  Email:     admin@estatemanagement.com<br>
  Password:  Admin@123456
</div>

<div class="warning">
  <strong>Important:</strong> If you run this script again after the admin already exists, it will print "Admin user already exists" — this is normal. Do not run it twice unless you need to reset the admin password.
</div>

<h2>4.1 Resetting the Admin Password</h2>

<p>If you need to reset the admin, delete the existing admin record and run the script again:</p>
<ol>
  <li>Open MongoDB Compass or your MongoDB client</li>
  <li>Connect to <code>mongodb://localhost:27017/estate-management</code></li>
  <li>Find the <strong>admins</strong> collection and delete the document</li>
  <li>Run <code>node scripts/createAdmin.js</code> again</li>
</ol>

<hr class="section-divider">

<!-- SECTION 5 -->
<h1 id="demo-data">5. Loading Demo Data</h1>

<p>The project includes a seed script that adds 28 demo properties (20 in Bengaluru, 8 in other cities) and 5 demo user accounts.</p>

<pre>cd backend
node scripts/seedAll.js --force</pre>

